<br>
Well said!  I agree, and I think most paladins agree, that warriors should have an edge on tanking.  I think mostly we are just arguing over the degree of superiority your edge should provide you.<br>
<br>
Bear in mind that a generic paladin, level 52-58 can tank for a group moderately well.  Depending on gear, he might be able to do almost as well as a warrior.  At 59 paladins get nice spell that will help them out tanking, and at 60, most paladins start to invest in AAXP.  HOWEVER, and this is pretty important, a paladin doesn't really become a threat to the warrior as group tank until he invests in several of the Melee Archetypal AA skills.  And a paladin can't really own the role of group healer until he has several Priest Archetypal AA skills.  Before that point, the paladin is similar to a warrior a few levels lower, but who can contribute some mana to the group.<br>
<br>
At any rate, I don't want to take away from the core point, which is that most paladins agree warriors should be able to tank better than us.  But the consensus is that warriors shouldn't be A LOT better than us.<br>
<br>
Fixing Taunt and mitigation seem to be the two things that really ought to be done to straighten out the high-end game.  <br>
<br>
Would a gradual decrease in the delay of the taunt skill to 2seconds at level 60 help warriors enough?  What about the oft-suggested &quot;armor mitigation factor&quot; where damage taken is modified based on armor type (heavy plate, light plate, chain, etc)?<br>
<br>
Perhaps these two in conjunction could boost warriors to a point where they would be happy without leaving paladins in the Dark Ages of Kunark again.<br>
<br>
